AGI - The US State Department has accused Russia of using a chemical agent, chloropicrine, against Ukrainian forces, in violation of the Convention on Chemical Weapons. According to Washington, moreover, Moscow would have used tear gas, of the type supplied to the anti-Soak Police, as "the tool of guerrilla", a further violation of the Convention. "The use of such chemicals is not an isolated incident > and is probably linked to the desire of Russian forces to hunt Ukrainian forces from fortified positions and gain tactical advantages on the battlefield," reads in a note.
&nbsp;
Meanwhile, the US Treasury has announced sanctions against 300 companies in Russia, China and other countries > accused of providing weapons or components useful to the Moscow war effort. "Today's actions will further disrupt and deteriore Russia's war efforts, striking its military industrial base and evasion networks that help to supply it," said the secretary, Janet Yellen. In the sights, there are people and companies involved in the energy, mining and metallurgical sectors of Moscow, along with individuals linked to the death of Russian opposition leader Aleksei Navalny.
&nbsp;
According to the United States National Institutes of Health, chloropicrine is used both as a weapon and as a pesticide. Russia claims to no longer possess a military chemical arsenal, but the country must face pressures for greater transparency on the alleged use of toxic weapons. Immediate reaction of the Kremlin: the spokesman Dmitri Peskov rejected the accusations by calling them "completely unfounded and undemonstrated". "Russia - it has added - has been and remains committed to respect its obligations under international law."
&nbsp;
As for the new American sanctions against Russia and individuals and entities in other countries - China first, but also Azerbaijan, India, Slovakia and Turkey - these will not affect relations between Moscow and them. "The United States continues to exert clear pressure on these countries. The companies are suffering, but this cannot stop the development of our bilateral relations» said Peskov. "These countries maintain their sovereignty and are interested in continuing to develop their relations with Russia", he stressed, ensuring that cooperation will continue and "so as to gradually minimize the risks arising from such hostile events"

