&nbsp;
Meanwhile, Israel reopened the only north-eastern passage of the Gaza Strip for the first time since October 7, allowing aid trucks to pass through Erez's checkpoint following the U.S. requests to do more to bring aid to the Strip. The reopening of the Erez Pass - which normally facilitates the passage of people, not supplies - has been one of the main demands of international humanitarian agencies for months. The checkpoint was largely destroyed by &nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; during the October 7 attack. Nearby, within Gaza, the army then found a huge tunnel of &nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; far enough to allow the passage of a car. The army said that about 30 trucks carrying food and medical supplies from Jordan entered via Erez on Wednesday, first undergoing "attention security check". &nbsp;<br> &nbsp;
Iran has decided a package of sanctions against American and British people and entities for supporting Israel in the war against Hamas and interventions in the Red Sea. The Islamic republic, acerrimous enemy of Israel, has made known the measures in a statement of its Foreign Ministry. The sanctions affect seven Americans, including General Bryan P. Fenton, commander of the U.S. Special Operations Command, and Deputy Admiral Brad Cooper, former commander of the fifth American Navy fleet. Among British officials and authorities, the Secretary of State for Defense Grant Shapps, British Army strategic commander James Hockenhull and British Royal Navy in the Red Sea. sanctions were also made against American companies Lockheed Martin and Chevron and British counterparts Elbit Systems, Parker Meggitt and Rafael UK. The measures include "the blocking of accounts and transactions in the Iranian financial and banking system, the blocking of assets within the jurisdiction of the Islamic Republic of Iran, as well as the ban on the release of visas and entry into Iran". &nbsp;

