AGI - The China National Space Administration (CNSA) announced the launch of the Chang'e 6 mission for this Friday. The spacecraft will be launched from the site of Wenchang, in the southern province of Hainan, using a carrier rocket Long March-5 Y8, reported the agency. The main objective of this mission is to collect for the first time samples from the hidden face of the Moon, a unexplored region that aroused great interest in the international scientific community. Chang'e 6 is directed to the Aitken-Polo Sud basin, an area with unique geological characteristics that could shed light on the origins and evolution of our satellite. The launch preparations are in the final stage, with the completion of a final test that involved all relevant systems. &nbsp;
&nbsp;
Chinese authorities have strengthened the weather forecast system to ensure the successful operation and have designed 10 alternative trajectories to make the most of the restricted launch window, which consists of two days and 50 minutes each. The Chang'e 6 probe consists of four components: an orbiter, a lander, an elevator and a return form. The elevator will have the crucial function of transporting the lunar samples collected from the lander to the lunar orbiter. Once there, the samples will be transferred to the return form, which will bring them back to Earth for lab analysis.
&nbsp;
With this mission, China aims to enter the narrow group of countries that have managed to collect samples of lunar material, following the footsteps of the United States and the former Soviet Union but surpassing them with the exploration of the hidden side of the Moon, which would mark a historic milestone. One of the key assumptions of this mission was the launch of the retransmission satellite Queqiao 2 on March 20. This satellite will facilitate communication between Chang'e 6 and Earth, ensuring efficient data transmission. The latest Chinese lunar probe, Chang'e 5, traveled to the satellite in 2020, where he collected 1,731 grams of soil samples. The Chang'e program (from the name of a goddess who according to Chinese legends lives on the Moon) began with the launch of a first probe in 2007. In recent years, Beijing has invested a lot in its space program and has marked important successes such as the landing of Chang'e 4 on the hidden side of the Moon in January 2019, another milestone in the history of space exploration. &nbsp;
